english:
  title: Farewell to Kim Jun, Rector of the Hongmungwan
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A man's body of seven feet is a gift from Heaven of the greatest magnitude. If one can understand words, nurture the vital force, and expand this greatest gift within, then standing firm in principle and maintaining integrity becomes unshakeable, responding to the world's demands with abundant ease. Unmoved by threats, unswayed by profit, placed in peril yet unconfused, entrusted with tangled affairs yet undoubting—when all things under Heaven cannot disturb the mind or shake the heart, one may dispel difficulties and untangle complexities from a thousand miles away while merely conversing and gesturing. How much more so when bearing a brief letter to cultivate old friendships in a land reachable by a single boat?

    Japan lies within the sea, where water routes are treacherous and distant. Envoys have rarely been able to exchange messages in timely fashion. Consider how our Sage Sovereign grasps the symbols of rule and governs the world. His voice and influence reach far, and the ocean's waves remain calm. Japan has frequently sent envoys to cultivate friendship. The Sovereign commands the Ministry of Rites: "Propriety means to give as well as receive. To receive without reciprocating is not propriety. Send envoys swiftly to return their courtesy." Thus Kim Jun was selected as Document Official for this mission. People said: "Kim Jun abandons the honor of serving in the Jade Archives to cross the perilous whale-filled seas where waters cannot be measured. Moreover, the land and climate suit him not, and language requires translators to be understood. Surely his heart harbors doubts about this journey."

    One day Kim Jun came to bid me farewell. Observing his countenance, I saw it warm and gracious. Hearing his words, I found them firm and steadfast, showing not a trace of despair or melancholy. Here truly is one who understands words and nurtures the vital force. He regards the vast ocean as level ground, boat and oar as bed and chair. Supporting the mission, he shall illuminate virtue and majesty, binding the two nations in lasting amity—this needs no divination to confirm.

    Moreover, Kim Jun is broadly learned with able brush, bold of talent and unbounded by constraint. Relying on the state's spiritual power, bearing loyalty and honor's mandate, he shall strike his oar against roaring waves, visit isle after isle, and reach the lands where the sun rises. Across endless, boundless miles the eye beholds, fish and dragons display their strange forms, islands reveal their wonders. The sun spreads its wings over the eastern sky, rainbows ignite the great void above. Heaven's countenance and ocean's light gleam golden, dazzling to behold—truly the world's greatest spectacle.

    Once Sima Qian's travels never left the central provinces, yet they increased his spirit and enriched his prose. Now Kim Jun's journey reaches far greater distances, his observations far grander vistas. What he shall gain surely transcends even Sima Qian's achievement. I shall wipe my eyes and await his return to inquire of these wonders.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The seven-foot body and cultivation of vital force (qi) reference Mencius's philosophy of moral development through understanding language and nurturing one's inherent nature.
  - key: ''
    value: The Hongmungwan (Hall of Vast Culture) was Korea's premier scholarly institution, comparable to a national academy.
  - key: ''
    value: Sima Qian (司馬遷, also known as Ssu-ma Ch'ien) was the renowned Han Dynasty historian and author of the Records of the Grand Historian, invoked here as the classical exemplar of the traveler-scholar whose experiences enriched his writing.
